In this posting:
[1] Michigan
[2] Pennsylvania

******
[1] Michigan
Date: Tue 27 Mar 2018
Source: MLive [edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/us-world/index.ssf/2018/03/cdc_second_flu_wave.html


The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reports that while flu season is winding down, a 2nd strain that is more severe in younger children remains prevalent.

In an update, the CDC says that reports of the influenza A virus are on the decline while reports of the influenza B virus were more prevalent. A spokesperson for the CDC told CNN that influenza B can be "just as severe" as influenza A, and that "we also know that influenza B tends to be more severe for younger children." Flu season is getting worse, highest level in nearly a decade.

According to a government report released [Fri 23 Mar 2018], 1 out of every 13 visits to doctor's offices last week was for fever, cough, or flu symptoms.

As of its latest update, the CDC reports that flu-related child deaths are up to 133 for the 2017-2018 flu season. There were 5 pediatric deaths reported between [10 and 17 Mar 2018] related to influenza B, and one related to influenza A. During this week, 2.7 percent of patients visiting a doctor's office complained of flu-like symptoms.

Michigan, and most of the Midwest, is listed as having low to minimal flu activity as of the CDC's most recent update from the week ending on [17 Mar 2018].

A little more than a month ago, the CDC along with the Food and Drug Administration reported that this year's [2018] flu vaccine had been 36 percent effective. While this number sounds low to some, both agencies reported that this level was "better than some might have predicted." In fact, this number was 19 percent higher than Canada's vaccine, and 26 percent higher than Australia's.

At this time, the influenza A strain had accounted for 75 percent of all cases. 2 Michigan cities ranked among most at-risk in US for flu, influenza Grand Rapids-Wyoming is listed in the very high at-risk group and Detroit can be found one rung below in the high at-risk group. The Doctors Report app reports in a news release it compiles its rankings using data from nearly one million doctors across the United States.

"However, because of the severity of this season, there have been questions raised about how well this year's flu vaccine worked," the FDA commissioner Scott Gottlieb said in a news release. "Although the initial report of 36 percent overall efficacy for this year's vaccine in the United States that has been reported by our colleagues at the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is better than some might have predicted, there is still clearly significant room for improvement.

"Because influenza viruses can change their genetic make-up rapidly during the course of a single year, seasonal influenza vaccines are unlike most other preventative vaccines, in that the strains contained in the vaccine constantly need to be adjusted based on the viruses that are expected to be in circulation."

[Byline: Benjamin Raven]

