******
[2] Pennsylvania
Date: Tue 27 Mar 2018
Source: Pennlive.com[edited]
http://www.pennlive.com/news/2018/03/pennsylvania_flu_cases_take_an.html


Pennsylvania's unusually-severe flu season peaked in February [2018], but cases rose slightly last week, likely because of a "B strain" of the flu, the Pennsylvania Department of Health reported [Tue 27 Mar 2018].

The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also noted a national increase in the B strain, with a CDC doctor telling CNN that B strains can be hard on young children, so parents should continue to be on the lookout for symptoms in their child.

The report from the Pennsylvania health department stated, "There is usually co-circulation of influenza viruses during any one season and it's not uncommon for there to be second waves of influenza B activity during an influenza season."

Still, the flu was far less prevalent during the week that ended [Sat 24 Mar 2018] than it was during the weeks surrounding the peak reached during the week ending [10 Feb 2018].

The peak-period was dominated by a flu strain called H3N2, an A strain known for causing an unusually high number of hospitalizations and deaths. A strains are generally considered more harmful than B strains.

As of [Sat 24 Mar 2018], A strains had accounted for about 71 percent of flu cases in Pennsylvania in the 2017-2018 flu season, with B strains accounting for about 26 percent.

As of [Sat 24 Mar 2018], 207 people in Pennsylvania had died of flu-related causes during the flu season that began in late October [2017] and is usually over by May, with 15 of the deaths reported last week [week of 19 Mar 2918]. For the year, 6 of the flu-related deaths have involved children.

Symptoms of A and B strains are similar, typically involving fever, congestion, fatigue, and muscle soreness. Most people recover at home with rest, drinking plenty of fluids and using over-the-counter pain relievers.

[Byline: David Wenner]

