[HealthMap/ProMED-mail map
Pennsylvania, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5717195,240

To date, more research has focused on influenza A than on influenza B. Current opinion of influenza B remains influenced by early studies that concluded that influenza B posed less of a disease burden than influenza A. Furthermore, because of the ability of influenza A to cause severe pandemics, it is more frequently a topic of press coverage than influenza B, reinforcing the perception that influenza B does not pose a serious threat to public health. In contrast to the popular view that influenza B has minimal impact, there are indications that the impact of influenza B is substantial (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3673513/).

Surveillance data from the United States and Europe suggest a potentially increasing burden of influenza B in recent years. This high variability in influenza B circulation may be attributable to variable population immunity and competition between the 2 co-circulating lineages of influenza B. Furthermore, influenza B-attributable primary respiratory and circulatory hospitalization rate in the United States was a substantial 81.4 per 100 000 -- midway between the primary respiratory and circulatory hospitalization rates for seasonal A (H1N1) and A (H3N2) at 55.9 and 99.0 per 100 000, respectively (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15367555).

Available medical literature shows that influenza B can pose a significant burden to the global population. The comprehensiveness and quality of reporting of influenza B can be substantially improved. Additional data regarding the incidence, clinical burden, and economic impact of influenza B would augment our understanding of the disease and assist in vaccine development. - Mod.UBA]
